<font color="#FF0000">POW/MIA ITEMS OF INTEREST</font><br>
<tt>Thu May 22 23:56:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Three items:<br><br>
1. From a petition to be addressed to the President under the sponsorship of the National League of Families:<br><br>
&quot;A recently declassified Special National Intelligence Estimate, plus subsequent assessments by the Defense Intelligence Agency and Joint Casualty Resolution Center as late as 1992, reveal that Vietnam, acting alone, can return the remains of 465-590 Americans still missing from the Vietnam War and help account for 225-370 more with real sharing of archival information.  Nothing has occurred to alter these facts.  You have often pledged that obtaining the fullest possible accounting for America's POWs/MIAs is your highest priority of relations with Vietnam and stated that the best way to achieve this was to lift the trade embargo and normalize relations.  It is not working.  We expect results, not just statements assuring us that all is well.  We urge you to press Vietnam to account for our POWs/MIAs now!  Only then can real normaization take place and we, the American people, really put behind us the divisiveness of the Vietnam War.&quot;<br><br>
2. Yesterday, May 21, in Hanoi in the presence of new American ambassador Pete Peterson, 7 sets of remains were turned over to the US by Vietnam.  Let's see if we get beyond this baby step.<br><br>
3. A POW/MIA memorial is to be built by the POW/MIA Awareness Committee of Camden &amp; Gloucester Counties in Cooper River Park, Camden County, New Jersey to honor the more than 90,000 POWs/MIAs that have not come home after WWI, WWII, Korea and Vietnam.  The 7 foot black granite marker has been designed by a Runnemede, NJ., stonemason.  It will be carved with the POW/MIA emblem and have the insignia of each service branch at the base.  For information, call Robert Jonas at (609)-845-1682.  
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


